I"¡<h3 id="introduction">Introduction</h3>
<p>We have already studied horizontal asymptotes. Some functions have more interesting behaviour at large values of $x$. We study the simplest extension of horizontal asymptote today, by looking at slant asymptotes, also known as linear asymptotes.</p>

<div class="example">
<b>Example:</b> Determine the slant asymptote of the function $$f(x) = \frac{2x^2 + 3}{x}$$
</div>

<div class="example">
<b>Example:</b> Determine the slant asymptote of the function $$f(x) = \frac{-2x^3+x^2+3}{3x^2+4}$$
</div>

<div class="example">
<b>Example:</b> Determine the slant asymptote of the function $$f(x) = \frac{xe^x + 1}{e^x + 2}$$
</div>
